    Key defect                                                                  
                                                                                
     • The program holds onto an iterator that is not guaranteed to stay valid  
       across mutations of the vector (push_back).                              
     • Dereferencing that iterator after the vector may have reallocated is     
       undefined behavior; ASan simply makes the violation visible.             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Preserve the value you need before any mutation, then use that value        
    later:                                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
         auto it = v.begin() + 2;          // points to element 3               
         int element = *it;                // <-- copy the value now            
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
         std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", element); // safe          
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Why it works: element is a plain int; copying a value has no side‑effects   
    and does not depend on the vector’s internal storage, so it remains valid   
    after reallocation.                                                         
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    More thorough root‑cause fix (design‑level)                                 
                                                                                
    If the intention is to keep an iterator that stays valid even after many    
    push_back operations, the current approach is fundamentally flawed because  
    no iterator into a std::vector is stable under reallocation. Choose a       
    container or strategy that provides stable referencing:                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Option                  Description              Trade‑off                 
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────   
     Reserve enough          v.reserve(v.size() +     Simple change, but only   
