    Recommended robust redesign (if the program’s logic permits):               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
         // Take a snapshot of the element we care about                        
         int element = v[2];                // or *(v.begin()+2);               
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
         std::printf("element via stable view: %d\n", element);                 
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or, if you truly need a reference that survives reallocation, allocate the  
    vector with enough reserved capacity once and never exceed it:              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::vector<int> v;                                                        
     v.reserve(1004);                     // enough for initial 4 + 1000        
     pushes                                                                     
     v = {1,2,3,4};                                                             
     auto it = v.begin() + 2;             // iterator now stable                
     for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                           
         v.push_back(i);                                                        
     }                                                                          
     std::printf("element via stable iter: %d\n", *it);                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Summary of what to do                                                       
                                                                                
     1 Identify the moment of invalidation – the iterator it becomes invalid    
       after the first push_back that triggers a reallocation.                  
     2 Never dereference an iterator after any operation that may reallocate    
       the container (any insertion, emplace, resize, shrink_to_fit, etc.).     
     3 Fix by either                                                            
        • copying the needed value before mutations (minimal change), or        
        • ensuring the container never reallocates (reserve or use a stable     
          container), or                                                        
        • re‑thinking the design to avoid holding onto raw iterators in the     
          first place.                                                          
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Apply the minimal fix first (copy the value before the loop). If the        
    project later requires keeping a stable “pointer” into the data, then       
    refactor to one of the more thorough solutions listed above (reserve        
    capacity or switch to a container with stable references). This will        
    eliminate the use‑after‑free and prevent the AddressSanitizer crash.        
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     • Minimal fix: copy *it into a local variable before the loop and use      
       that variable when printing.                                             
     • Root‑cause fix: redesign the code to avoid using iterators that may be   
       invalidated; either reserve sufficient capacity, use a container with    
       stable references, or operate on indices/values rather than iterators.   
                                                                                
